<file path="docs/provision-pattern/018-ai-gateway-simulator-benchmark/README.md">
# 018 - AI Gateway Simulator Benchmark

This example is the VFlow blackbox benchmark counterpart of the older
`examples-vil/001b-vilapp-ai-gw-benchmark` scenario.

It is intentionally shaped as a workflow-product benchmark:

```text
wrk -> VFlow webhook -> HTTP streaming connector -> local AI simulator -> JSON response
```

The benchmark does not call VFlow admin, provision, runtime-console, or
operator endpoints during the measured path. Workflow upload and activation are
setup steps only.

## Runtime Contract

| Item | Value |
|---|---|
| Webhook route | `POST /api/gw/stream` |
| Upstream simulator | `http://127.0.0.1:4545/v1/chat/completions` |
| Connector | `vastar.http` |
| Streaming dialect | `openai` |
| Response shape | `{ "content": "..." }` |

## Request

```bash
curl -sS \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d @payloads/trigger.json \
  http://127.0.0.1:18080/api/gw/stream
```

Expected response:

```json
{
  "content": "..."
}
```

## Benchmark Tools

Use the benchmark script from the VFlow benchmark folder:

```bash
wrk -t4 -c64 -d30s \
  -s ../../../benchmark-vflow/wrk-scripts/018-ai-gateway-simulator.lua \
  http://127.0.0.1:18080/api/gw/stream
```

Run the same scenario with Vastar Bench:

```bash
vastar -c 300 -n 5000 -m POST -T application/json \
  -D ../../../benchmark-vflow/requests/018-ai-gateway-simulator.json \
  http://127.0.0.1:18080/api/gw/stream
```

The provisionable benchmark harness runs both tools against this route and uses
`c=300` for this scenario by default:

```bash
SCENARIOS="018-ai-gateway-simulator" \
MODE=requests \
REQUESTS=5000 \
TOOLS="wrk vastar" \
bash ../../../benchmark-vflow/run-primary.sh
```

Record the simulator version, VFlow build profile, CPU governor, CPU model,
logical CPUs, RAM, swap, kernel version, concurrency, duration, latency
percentiles, request rate, error rate, and runtime RSS with every report.
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/018-ai-gateway-simulator-benchmark/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: ai-gateway-simulator-benchmark
  name: "AI Gateway Simulator Benchmark"
  description: |
    Blackbox workflow benchmark for a local AI gateway path.

    Measured path:
      wrk -> VFlow webhook -> vastar.http streaming connector ->
      ai-endpoint-simulator -> VFlow chunked stream

    This mirrors the historic 2026-04-19 vflow_http benchmark workflow shape:
      webhook -> vastar.http streaming connector with OpenAI json_tap ->
      literal upstream body -> chunked response.

    The setup phase may upload and activate this workflow through the runtime
    admin API, but the benchmark itself must only hit the webhook route.

spec:
  activities:
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: webhook
        runtime_mode: fastpath
        webhook_config:
          path: /api/gw/stream
          method: POST
        response_framing: chunked
        end_activity: respond
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    - id: call_simulator
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: vastar.http
        operation: post
        streaming: true
        dialect: openai
        json_tap: "choices[0].delta.content"
        timeout_ms: 30000
      input_mappings:
        - target: url
          source:
            language: literal
            source: "http://127.0.0.1:4545/v1/chat/completions"
        - target: body
          source:
            language: literal
            source: '{"model":"gpt-4","messages":[{"role":"user","content":"Benchmark performance test via VIL"}],"stream":true}'
      output_variable: llm_result

    - id: respond
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response:
          language: vil-expr
          source: '{"content": llm_result.content}'

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    - { id: f1, from: { node: trigger }, to: { node: call_simulator } }
    - { id: f2, from: { node: call_simulator }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f3, from: { node: respond }, to: { node: end } }
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/019-compute-starlark/README.md">
# 019 Compute/Starlark

Scope: local compile contract plus runtime-ready workflow shape.

This example documents the public `activity_type: Compute` authoring surface
for hand-written Starlark/V-Starlark compute. It keeps the workflow
side-effect-free so it can stay in the default examples regression runner.

Expected behavior:

- The webhook receives a JSON body containing `subtotal` and `tiers`.
- `pricing` maps those values into the Compute `ctx` dict.
- The Starlark `run(ctx)` function chooses the matching discount tier and
  returns a quote object.
- `respond` returns the computed quote to the trigger.

Example input:

```json
{
  "subtotal": 1500,
  "tiers": [
    { "min": 500, "pct": 5 },
    { "min": 1000, "pct": 10 }
  ]
}
```

Expected compute result:

```json
{
  "base": 1500,
  "discount_pct": 10,
  "final_price": 1350
}
```
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/019-compute-starlark/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: compute-starlark
  name: "P1 Compute/Starlark public example"
  description: |
    Runtime-local workflow example for side-effect-free Starlark/V-Starlark
    compute. This demonstrates the public Compute activity config without
    requiring external infra or cloud control-plane traffic.

spec:
  activities:
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: webhook
        runtime_mode: fastpath
        webhook_config: { path: /examples/compute-starlark, method: POST }
        response_framing: length_prefixed
        end_activity: respond
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    - id: pricing
      activity_type: Compute
      compute_config:
        language: v-starlark
        source: |
          def run(ctx):
              base = ctx["base"]
              discount = 0
              for tier in ctx["tiers"]:
                  if base >= tier["min"]:
                      discount = tier["pct"]
              return {
                  "base": base,
                  "discount_pct": discount,
                  "final_price": base * (100 - discount) // 100,
              }
        entry_fn: run
        budget_profile: balanced
        timeout_ms: 3000
      input_mappings:
        - target: base
          source: { language: spv1, source: '$.trigger_payload.body.subtotal' }
        - target: tiers
          source: { language: spv1, source: '$.trigger_payload.body.tiers' }
      output_variable: price_quote

    - id: respond
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response:
          language: spv1
          source: '$.price_quote'

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    - { id: f1, from: { node: trigger }, to: { node: pricing } }
    - { id: f2, from: { node: pricing }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f3, from: { node: respond }, to: { node: end } }
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/020-retail-order-intake/README.md">
# 020 - Retail Order Intake

Business scenario: a storefront receives a cart, validates the payload,
normalizes the order, routes high-value carts to review, and reserves inventory
for normal carts.

This is the first proper business example after the schema matrices. It is not
only a node catalog: it documents the expected request, response paths, and
side-effect boundary.

## Runtime Route

`POST /examples/retail/orders`

## Example Request

```json
{
  "customer_id": "cust_1001",
  "currency": "IDR",
  "subtotal": 425000,
  "items": [
    { "sku": "COF-250", "qty": 2, "unit_price": 120000 },
    { "sku": "MUG-001", "qty": 1, "unit_price": 185000 }
  ]
}
```

## Expected Paths

| Path | Condition | Expected behavior |
|---|---|---|
| Accepted | Valid payload and `subtotal < 1000000` | Calls the local inventory mock and responds with `status: accepted`. |
| Review | Valid payload and `subtotal >= 1000000` | Does not reserve inventory; responds with `status: manual_review`. |
| Rejected | Validate activity fails | Uses the error edge and responds with `status: rejected`. |

## Feature Coverage

- Webhook trigger and EndTrigger response.
- JSON-schema-like `Validate` activity.
- `Transform` data shaping with V-CEL mappings.
- `LoopForEach` for order-line iteration shape.
- `Exclusive` routing for business decisioning.
- HTTP `Connector` with `persistence: ssot` for inventory reservation.
- Error edge from validation failure.

## Local Mock Contract

The inventory connector expects a local mock when running the workflow end to
end:

`POST http://127.0.0.1:18020/inventory/reserve`

Expected mock response:

```json
{
  "reservation_id": "resv_020_001",
  "expires_in_seconds": 900
}
```
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/020-retail-order-intake/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: retail-order-intake
  name: "Retail Order Intake"
  description: |
    Storefront order intake workflow. Validates a cart, normalizes the payload,
    routes high-value carts to manual review, and reserves inventory for
    normal carts. This example is runtime-local and does not depend on
    vflow-cloud.
  dialect: vflow
  tags: [example, p0, retail, validation, routing]

spec:
  durability:
    enabled: true
    default_mode: eventual

  activities:
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: webhook
        route: /examples/retail/orders
        webhook_config: { path: /examples/retail/orders, method: POST }
        response_framing: length_prefixed
        end_activity: respond-accepted
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    - id: validate_order
      activity_type: Validate
      validate_config:
        input: "$.trigger_payload.body"
        schema:
          required: [customer_id, currency, subtotal, items]
          properties:
            customer_id: { type: string, min_length: 3 }
            currency: { type: string, min_length: 3, max_length: 3 }
            subtotal: { type: number, min: 1 }
            items: { type: array, min: 1 }
      output_variable: validated_order

    - id: normalize_order
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: order
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: '{"customer_id": trigger_payload.body.customer_id, "currency": trigger_payload.body.currency, "subtotal": trigger_payload.body.subtotal, "items": trigger_payload.body.items, "item_count": size(trigger_payload.body.items), "risk_band": trigger_payload.body.subtotal >= 1000000 ? "review" : "standard"}'
      output_variable: order_context

    - id: compute_review_hint
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: hint
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: '{"review_required": order_context.subtotal >= 1000000, "reason": order_context.subtotal >= 1000000 ? "high_value_order" : "standard_order"}'
      output_variable: review_hint

    - id: process_lines
      activity_type: LoopForEach
      loop_config:
        collection: "$.order_context.items"
        item_variable: item
        mode: sequential
        max_iterations: 100

    - id: inspect_line
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: sku
          source: { language: v-cel, source: 'item.sku' }
        - target: quantity
          source: { language: v-cel, source: 'item.qty' }
      output_variable: last_line

    - id: route_order
      activity_type: Exclusive
      description: "High-value orders require manual review before inventory reservation."

    - id: reserve_inventory
      activity_type: Connector
      persistence: ssot
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: vastar.http
        operation: post
        timeout_ms: 3000
        retry_policy:
          max_attempts: 2
          base_delay_ms: 100
          max_delay_ms: 500
          backoff_factor: 2.0
      input_mappings:
        - target: url
          source: { language: literal, source: "http://127.0.0.1:18020/inventory/reserve" }
        - target: body
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: '{"customer_id": order_context.customer_id, "items": order_context.items, "idempotency_key": "retail-order-intake"}'
      output_variable: inventory_reservation

    - id: accepted_response
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: response
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: '{"status": "accepted", "customer_id": order_context.customer_id, "subtotal": order_context.subtotal, "reservation": inventory_reservation}'
      output_variable: final_response

    - id: review_response
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: response
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: '{"status": "manual_review", "customer_id": order_context.customer_id, "subtotal": order_context.subtotal, "reason": review_hint.reason}'
      output_variable: review_response

    - id: rejected_response
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: response
          source:
            language: literal
            source: '{"status":"rejected","reason":"invalid_order_payload"}'
      output_variable: rejected_response

    - id: respond-accepted
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response: { language: spv1, source: "$.final_response" }

    - id: respond-review
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response: { language: spv1, source: "$.review_response" }

    - id: respond-rejected
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response: { language: spv1, source: "$.rejected_response" }

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    - { id: f01, from: { node: trigger }, to: { node: validate_order } }
    - { id: f02, from: { node: validate_order }, to: { node: normalize_order } }
    - { id: f03, from: { node: normalize_order }, to: { node: compute_review_hint } }
    - { id: f04, from: { node: compute_review_hint }, to: { node: process_lines } }
    - { id: f05, from: { node: process_lines }, to: { node: inspect_line } }
    - { id: f06, from: { node: inspect_line }, to: { node: process_lines } }
    - { id: f07, from: { node: process_lines }, to: { node: route_order }, type: default }
    - { id: f08, from: { node: route_order }, to: { node: review_response }, condition: "order_context.subtotal >= 1000000", priority: 20 }
    - { id: f09, from: { node: route_order }, to: { node: reserve_inventory }, type: default, priority: 0 }
    - { id: f10, from: { node: reserve_inventory }, to: { node: accepted_response } }
    - { id: f11, from: { node: accepted_response }, to: { node: respond-accepted } }
    - { id: f12, from: { node: review_response }, to: { node: respond-review } }
    - { id: f13, type: error, from: { node: validate_order }, to: { node: rejected_response } }
    - { id: f14, from: { node: rejected_response }, to: { node: respond-rejected } }
    - { id: f15, from: { node: respond-accepted }, to: { node: end } }
    - { id: f16, from: { node: respond-review }, to: { node: end } }
    - { id: f17, from: { node: respond-rejected }, to: { node: end } }

  variables:
    - { name: trigger_payload, type: object }
    - { name: order_context, type: object }
    - { name: review_hint, type: object }
    - { name: inventory_reservation, type: object }
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/021-payments-risk-routing/README.md">
# 021 - Payments Risk Routing

Business scenario: a payment authorization request is validated, scored by
VDICL rules, routed to a low-risk authorization rail, routed to step-up
authentication, or declined before any side effect.

This example documents the side-effect posture explicitly: payment connectors
must be idempotent and `persistence: ssot` because retries and operator retry
can otherwise duplicate authorizations.

## Runtime Route

`POST /examples/payments/authorize`

## Example Request

```json
{
  "payment_id": "pay_1001",
  "idempotency_key": "pay_1001_attempt_1",
  "amount": 125000,
  "currency": "IDR",
  "card_bin": "411111",
  "country": "ID",
  "merchant_category": "coffee"
}
```

## Expected Paths

| Path | Condition | Expected behavior |
|---|---|---|
| Authorize | `risk_result.decision == "ACCEPT"` | Calls the local payment auth mock and returns `status: authorized`. |
| Step-up | `risk_result.decision == "CHALLENGE_MFA"` | Calls the local 3DS mock and returns `status: challenge_required`. |
| Decline | Default route | Does not call external payment rails and returns `status: declined`. |
| Failure | Payment connector fails | Error edge returns `status: authorization_failed`. |

## Feature Coverage

- Webhook trigger with a route-level rate-limit hint.
- Validate activity for payment payload.
- VRule / VDICL business decisioning.
- Exclusive routing by rule decision.
- HTTP Connector with explicit retry policy and `persistence: ssot`.
- Side-effect warning documented in the example itself.
- Error edge for payment rail failure.

`rules/payment_risk_routing_v1.vdicl` and
`schemas/payment_risk_fact_v1.yaml` are used by the live-safe smoke harness to
compile the actual VDICL pack before triggering this workflow.

## Local Mock Contracts

Authorization mock:

`POST http://127.0.0.1:18021/payments/authorize`

Expected mock response:

```json
{
  "authorization_id": "auth_021_001",
  "approved": true
}
```

3DS mock:

`POST http://127.0.0.1:18021/payments/3ds/challenge`

Expected mock response:

```json
{
  "challenge_id": "3ds_021_001",
  "redirect_url": "https://issuer.test/challenge/3ds_021_001"
}
```
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/021-payments-risk-routing/rules/payment_risk_routing_v1.vdicl">
schema_ref:
  path: "../schemas/payment_risk_fact_v1.yaml"
  namespace: "examples.payments"
  entity: "payment_risk_fact"
  version: 1
hit_policy: PRIORITY
rules:
  - id: "PAYMENT_BLOCKED_CATEGORY"
    priority: 0
    enabled: true
    description: "Reject categories that are explicitly blocked by the merchant risk policy."
    when: "trigger_payload.body.merchant_category == 'blocked'"
    then:
      - kind: EMIT
        severity: ERROR
        code: "PAYMENT_BLOCKED_CATEGORY"
        field: "trigger_payload.body.merchant_category"
        msg: "Merchant category is blocked"
      - kind: ADD_SCORE
        score_delta: 100
      - kind: SET_DECISION
        decision: REJECT

  - id: "PAYMENT_STEP_UP_CROSS_BORDER_OR_HIGH_VALUE"
    priority: 10
    enabled: true
    description: "Require cardholder challenge for high-value or cross-border payments."
    when: "trigger_payload.body.amount >= 20000000 OR trigger_payload.body.country != 'ID'"
    then:
      - kind: EMIT
        severity: WARN
        code: "PAYMENT_STEP_UP_REQUIRED"
        field: "trigger_payload.body.amount"
        msg: "Step-up authentication required"
      - kind: ADD_SCORE
        score_delta: 40
      - kind: SET_DECISION
        decision: CHALLENGE_MFA

  - id: "PAYMENT_STANDARD_APPROVE"
    priority: 100
    enabled: true
    description: "Approve standard low-risk payments."
    when: "trigger_payload.body.amount >= 1"
    then:
      - kind: ADD_SCORE
        score_delta: 0
      - kind: SET_DECISION
        decision: ACCEPT
</file>

