<file path="docs/provision-pattern/063-vflow-gateway-vstarlark/proto/gateway.proto">
// Combined proto for 062 (passthrough) + 063 (vflow gateway).
//
// `Gateway/Passthrough` (062) is the shared upstream both gateways
// forward to. `GatewayProxy/Passthrough` (063) is the vflow gateway
// front-end that performs light V-Starlark validation and forwards
// the request via the gRPC connector to `Gateway/Passthrough`.
//
// Same `GatewayMessage` type both ways so the head-to-head bench
// against Envoy + Lua filter can hold the wire format constant.

syntax = "proto3";

package examples;

// 062 endpoint — pure passthrough.
service Gateway {
  rpc Passthrough(GatewayMessage) returns (GatewayMessage);
}

// 063 endpoint — vflow gateway with V-Starlark validation +
// gRPC connector forwarding to Gateway/Passthrough.
service GatewayProxy {
  rpc Passthrough(GatewayMessage) returns (GatewayMessage);
}

message GatewayMessage {
  string tenant_id = 1;
  string trace_id  = 2;
  string payload   = 3;
}
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/063-vflow-gateway-vstarlark/README.md">
# 063 vflow Gateway with V-Starlark + gRPC Connector (FASTPATH)

Apple-to-apple comparator for **Envoy + Lua filter** as gRPC gateway.
This workflow plays the role of a light gRPC API-gateway with full
**V-Starlark business logic** mirroring what an Envoy Lua filter
would do — same auth check, same tenant validation, same trace-id
normalization, same response shaping.

## Architecture

```
                ┌────────────────────────────┐
client ───────► │ 063 GatewayProxy           │ ──┐
   gRPC         │  - V-Starlark gateway_logic│   │ vastar.grpc
                │    (auth, tenant, trace)   │   │ connector
                │  - vastar.grpc forward     │   │ (await response)
                │  - V-Starlark shape_resp   │   │
                │  - v-cel proto_encode      │   │
                │  FASTPATH RUNTIME          │   │
                └────────────────────────────┘   │
                          ▲                       ▼
                          │              ┌─────────────────┐
                          │              │ 062 Gateway     │
                          └──────────────│  fastpath       │
                                         │  passthrough    │
                                         └─────────────────┘
```

Both 062 (upstream) and 063 (gateway) live on the same vflow process,
exposed on `examples.Gateway/Passthrough` and
`examples.GatewayProxy/Passthrough` respectively (port 50071).

## Activities (V-Starlark dominant)

| # | Type | Logic |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Trigger (gRPC, fastpath) | `examples.GatewayProxy/Passthrough`, body=`GatewayMessage` |
| 2 | **Compute (V-Starlark)** | `gateway_logic`: auth check (api-key), tenant validation, trace-id normalization |
| 3 | Connector (gRPC unary) | `vastar.grpc` → `examples.Gateway/Passthrough` on 127.0.0.1:50071 |
| 4 | **Compute (V-Starlark)** | `shape_response`: gateway-side response shaping (mirror of `envoy_on_response`) |
| 5 | Transform (v-cel) | `proto_encode(...)` JSON → `GatewayMessage` proto bytes |
| 6 | EndTrigger | `bytes_ref` to encoded bytes |
| 7 | End | |

## Why fastpath needs the Connector restriction lifted

Pre-2026-05-03, fastpath plan-builder rejected `Connector` activities
on the response path with the error:

> "fastpath response path does not support Connector activity (...);
> Connector is allowed only on detached branches for per-full-payload
> side effects"

That was a vflow runtime defect — fastpath should never silently
disable functionality the user can author. The restriction was
lifted in `crates/vflow_server/src/vflow_http_exec.rs`:

- `dispatch_fastpath_connector_node` now async with two modes:
  - **await-response** (response path): inline await; decode upstream
    response into `output_var`; downstream nodes consume the real bytes.
  - **fire-and-forget** (detached side branches): existing tokio::spawn,
    placeholder `{"status":"queued"}` to output_var.
- `run_fastpath_transform_graph` made async; cascade through call sites.
- Plan-builder annotates each Connector node with `await_response`
  based on whether it's reachable from Trigger without crossing a
  detached edge.

**Performance impact**: 5.5× speedup for this workflow:
- Standard runtime (pre-fix forced): 1,943 RPS
- Fastpath (post-fix): **10,601 RPS** (peak at c=512)

## Bench results

See `benchmark-vflow/2026-05-03-grpc-gateway-vflow-vs-envoy.md` for
full 4-cell head-to-head with shared upstream.

| Cell | Setup | Peak RPS | µs/req | Overhead vs A |
|---|---|---:|---:|---:|
| A | Direct 062 (no gateway) | 42,939 | 23.3 | baseline |
| B | Envoy plain proxy → 062 | 28,054 | 35.6 | +12 µs |
| **C** | **vflow 063 fastpath gateway** | **10,601** | **94.3** | **+71 µs** |
| D | Envoy + Lua filter → 062 | 28,812 | 34.7 | +11 µs |

**Honest assessment**: for thin gRPC gateways (validate header,
forward, shape response), Envoy still wins by ~3×. vflow gateway
makes sense when the gateway is doing real workflow work — multi-
upstream enrichment, durable state lookups, conditional routing
with V-Rule, audit emission to NATS/ClickHouse, retries, etc.

## Reproduction

Server start (build vflow-server with `--features v-starlark`):
```bash
mkdir -p $STATE_DIR
echo '{"enabled":true,"port":50071}' > $STATE_DIR/grpc_server.json
VFLOW_PORT=18193 VFLOW_PIPELINE_PORT=18194 \
VFLOW_STATE_DIR=$STATE_DIR \
VFLOW_AUDIT_EMITTER=none VIL_LOG_OFF=1 \
vflow-server &
```

Workflow setup:
```bash
# Upload combined proto FIRST (both Gateway + GatewayProxy services)
curl -sS -X POST http://127.0.0.1:18193/api/admin/proto/upload \
  -H 'X-VFlow-Proto-File: gateway.proto' \
  --data-binary @./proto/gateway.proto

# Upload upstream 062
curl -sS -X POST http://127.0.0.1:18193/api/admin/workflow/upload \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/yaml' \
  --data-binary @../062-fastpath-grpc-passthrough/workflow.yaml

# Upload 063 (this workflow)
curl -sS -X POST http://127.0.0.1:18193/api/admin/workflow/upload \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/yaml' \
  --data-binary @./workflow.yaml

# Re-upload proto to refresh route registration
curl -sS -X POST http://127.0.0.1:18193/api/admin/proto/upload \
  -H 'X-VFlow-Proto-File: gateway.proto' \
  --data-binary @./proto/gateway.proto

# Smoke
grpcurl -plaintext \
  -import-path ./proto -proto gateway.proto \
  -d '{"tenant_id":"acme","trace_id":"t-001","payload":"hello"}' \
  127.0.0.1:50071 examples.GatewayProxy/Passthrough

# Bench at saturation point
ghz --insecure --proto ./proto/gateway.proto --import-paths ./proto \
    --call examples.GatewayProxy/Passthrough \
    --total 30000 --concurrency 512 --connections 32 \
    -d '{"tenant_id":"acme","trace_id":"t-001","payload":"hello"}' \
    127.0.0.1:50071
```

## Files

- `proto/gateway.proto` — combined proto with both `Gateway` (062) and `GatewayProxy` (063) services
- `gateway.desc.b64` — pre-computed FileDescriptorSet (base64) for the gRPC connector
- `workflow.yaml` — the gateway workflow (fastpath, V-Starlark business logic)
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/063-vflow-gateway-vstarlark/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: vflow-gateway-vstarlark
  name: "vflow Gateway with V-Starlark validation + gRPC connector forward"
  description: |
    Head-to-head with `Envoy + Lua filter` proxying to the same upstream.
    This workflow plays the role of a light gRPC API-gateway. **All
    business logic lives in V-Starlark** (apple-to-apple with the Lua
    filter on the Envoy side); v-cel only appears in narrow plumbing
    roles (binding adapter into V-Starlark `ctx`, and the
    `proto_encode` serialization helper).

      1. Receives `examples.GatewayProxy/Passthrough` over gRPC.
      2. **`gateway_logic` (V-Starlark)** — validates api-key header,
         validates tenant_id presence, normalizes trace_id, builds
         the upstream request payload.
      3. `forward` (gRPC connector) — calls `examples.Gateway/Passthrough`
         on 127.0.0.1:50071.
      4. **`shape_response` (V-Starlark)** — gateway-side response
         shaping (symmetric with request shaping; mirror of
         `envoy_on_response` in Lua).
      5. `encode_response` (v-cel `proto_encode`) — pure
         JSON→protobuf serialization (not business logic).
      6. EndTrigger via `bytes_ref`.

  dialect: vflow
  tags: [example, p0, grpc, gateway, vstarlark, connector, bench]

spec:
  activities:
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: grpc
        runtime_mode: fastpath
        grpc:
          service: "examples.GatewayProxy"
          method: "Passthrough"
          body_schema: "examples.GatewayMessage"
        response_framing: length_prefixed
        end_activity: respond
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    # Business logic in V-Starlark: read whole body, validate auth +
    # tenant, normalize the upstream request payload. This is the
    # gateway's "scripted gateway logic" — apple-to-apple with the
    # Envoy Lua filter that does the same kind of work.
    - id: gateway_logic
      activity_type: Compute
      compute_config:
        language: v-starlark
        source: |
          def run(ctx):
              # Light auth: api-key header must be either empty
              # (open) or match a known value. Mirrors Envoy Lua's
              # `headers:get("x-api-key")` compare.
              api_key = ctx["api_key"]
              if api_key and api_key != "demo-key":
                  return {
                      "ok": False,
                      "reason": "invalid api key",
                      "request": None,
                  }

              # Tenant validation
              tenant = ctx["tenant_id"]
              if not tenant:
                  return {
                      "ok": False,
                      "reason": "missing tenant_id",
                      "request": None,
                  }

              # Normalize: ensure trace_id is set (auto-generate if
              # missing — typical gateway responsibility)
              trace = ctx["trace_id"]
              if not trace:
                  trace = "trace-" + tenant

              # Build the upstream request payload
              return {
                  "ok": True,
                  "request": {
                      "tenant_id": tenant,
                      "trace_id":  trace,
                      "payload":   ctx["payload"],
                  },
              }
        entry_fn: run
        budget_profile: none
        timeout_ms: 1000
      input_mappings:
        # Each proto-bound field flows in as a typed scalar; the
        # proto-field tier in fastpath dispatches these without
        # entering the v-cel VM. Same pattern as 048.
        - target: tenant_id
          source: { language: v-cel, source: 'trigger_body.tenant_id' }
        - target: trace_id
          source: { language: v-cel, source: 'trigger_body.trace_id' }
        - target: payload
          source: { language: v-cel, source: 'trigger_body.payload' }
        - target: api_key
          source: { language: spv1, source: "$.trigger_payload.headers.x-api-key" }
      output_variable: gateway

    - id: forward
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: vastar.grpc
        operation: call
        timeout_ms: 5000
      input_mappings:
        - target: endpoint
          source: { language: literal, source: "http://127.0.0.1:50071" }
        - target: descriptor_set_b64
          source:
            language: literal
            source: ""
        - target: service
          source: { language: literal, source: "examples.Gateway" }
        - target: method
          source: { language: literal, source: "Passthrough" }
        # Use the V-Starlark-prepared payload, NOT the raw trigger body
        - target: request
          source: { language: spv1, source: "$.gateway.request" }
      output_variable: upstream_response

    # Final response shaping in V-Starlark too — the gateway can
    # add gateway-side metadata (e.g. trace_id propagation) before
    # returning. Equivalent to envoy_on_response in Lua.
    - id: shape_response
      activity_type: Compute
      compute_config:
        language: v-starlark
        source: |
          def run(ctx):
              # Pass-through, but explicitly through V-Starlark so
              # the response-shaping step is symmetric with the
              # request-shaping step (and with envoy_on_response
              # in the Envoy Lua filter).
              return {
                  "tenant_id": ctx["tenant_id"],
                  "trace_id":  ctx["trace_id"],
                  "payload":   ctx["payload"],
              }
        entry_fn: run
        budget_profile: none
        timeout_ms: 1000
      input_mappings:
        - target: tenant_id
          source: { language: spv1, source: "$.upstream_response.tenant_id" }
        - target: trace_id
          source: { language: spv1, source: "$.upstream_response.trace_id" }
        - target: payload
          source: { language: spv1, source: "$.upstream_response.payload" }
      output_variable: shaped

    # Pure plumbing: encode the V-Starlark-shaped JSON to proto
    # bytes. This is serialization, not business logic — kept in
    # v-cel `proto_encode` because that's its dedicated job.
    - id: encode_response
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: encoded_response
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: >
              proto_encode(
                {
                  "name": "GatewayMessage",
                  "fields": [
                    {"name": "tenant_id", "number": 1, "type": "string"},
                    {"name": "trace_id",  "number": 2, "type": "string"},
                    {"name": "payload",   "number": 3, "type": "string"}
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "tenant_id": shaped.tenant_id,
                  "trace_id":  shaped.trace_id,
                  "payload":   shaped.payload
                }
              )
      output_variable: encoded_response

    - id: respond
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response:
          language: bytes_ref
          source: "encoded_response"

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    - { id: f1, from: { node: trigger },         to: { node: gateway_logic } }
    - { id: f2, from: { node: gateway_logic },   to: { node: forward } }
    - { id: f3, from: { node: forward },         to: { node: shape_response } }
    - { id: f4, from: { node: shape_response },  to: { node: encode_response } }
    - { id: f5, from: { node: encode_response }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f6, from: { node: respond },         to: { node: end } }

  variables:
    - { name: trigger_payload,   type: object }
    - { name: gateway,           type: object }
    - { name: upstream_response, type: object }
    - { name: shaped,            type: object }
    - { name: encoded_response,  type: string }
</file>

