<file path="docs/provision-pattern/064-vflow-gateway-plain/proto/gateway.proto">
// Combined proto for 062 (passthrough) + 063 (V-Starlark gateway)
// + 064 (plain proxy gateway). Three services share `GatewayMessage`.
//
// 062 — `Gateway/Passthrough` is the shared upstream both gateways
//       forward to.
// 063 — `GatewayProxy/Passthrough` is the V-Starlark-scripted gateway.
// 064 — `GatewayPlain/Passthrough` is the plain forwarder gateway
//       (no scripting; isolates Connector + proto-encode overhead
//       so the V-Starlark vs Lua scripting cost can be measured
//       cleanly by subtraction).

syntax = "proto3";

package examples;

// 062 endpoint — pure passthrough.
service Gateway {
  rpc Passthrough(GatewayMessage) returns (GatewayMessage);
}

// 063 endpoint — vflow gateway with V-Starlark validation +
// gRPC connector forwarding.
service GatewayProxy {
  rpc Passthrough(GatewayMessage) returns (GatewayMessage);
}

// 064 endpoint — vflow plain forwarder. No scripting. Connector +
// proto_encode only. Apple-to-apple with Envoy plain proxy (B cell).
service GatewayPlain {
  rpc Passthrough(GatewayMessage) returns (GatewayMessage);
}

message GatewayMessage {
  string tenant_id = 1;
  string trace_id  = 2;
  string payload   = 3;
}
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/064-vflow-gateway-plain/README.md">
# 064 vflow Plain Gateway (no scripting)

Apple-to-apple comparator for **Envoy plain proxy** (no Lua filter).
This workflow is the *minimal* vflow gRPC gateway: just Connector
forward + proto_encode response. **No V-Starlark, no validation,
no scripting** — pure proxy plumbing.

## Why this exists

063 (V-Starlark) vs Envoy + Lua isn't quite apple-to-apple because
the comparison conflates two costs:
- **Structural proxy cost** (Connector framework, proto codec, runtime dispatch)
- **Scripting language cost** (V-Starlark interpreter vs Lua interpreter)

064 isolates the structural cost. Compare:
- 064 vs Envoy plain (B) → vflow proxy plumbing vs Envoy proxy plumbing
- 063 vs 064 → V-Starlark cost (in vflow context)
- D vs B → Lua cost (in Envoy context)

## Activities

| # | Type | Logic |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Trigger (gRPC, fastpath) | `examples.GatewayPlain/Passthrough`, body=`GatewayMessage` |
| 2 | Transform (v-cel) | `build_request`: extract trigger fields into JSON object |
| 3 | Connector (gRPC unary) | `vastar.grpc` forward to `examples.Gateway/Passthrough` |
| 4 | Transform (v-cel) | `proto_encode(...)` JSON → `GatewayMessage` proto bytes |
| 5 | EndTrigger | `bytes_ref` to encoded bytes |
| 6 | End | |

No Compute / V-Starlark anywhere. Each step is irreducible plumbing
required for vflow to act as a gRPC gateway.

## Bench results (5-cell head-to-head)

c=512 conn=32, total=30k, peak of 3 runs:

| Cell | Setup | Peak RPS | µs/req | Overhead vs A |
|---|---|---:|---:|---:|
| A | Direct 062 (no gateway) | 45,649 | 21.9 | baseline |
| B | Envoy plain proxy → 062 | 31,492 | 31.8 | +9.9 µs |
| **E (this)** | **vflow 064 plain → 062** | **11,291** | 88.6 | **+66.7 µs** |
| C | vflow 063 + V-Starlark → 062 | 10,963 | 91.2 | +69.3 µs |
| D | Envoy + Lua → 062 | 27,550 | 36.3 | +14.4 µs |

## Key finding: scripting language is NOT the bottleneck

| Comparison | Cost added by scripting |
|---|---:|
| **D − B** = Envoy + Lua − Envoy plain | **+4.5 µs** (Lua filter cost) |
| **C − E** = vflow + V-Starlark − vflow plain | **+2.6 µs** (V-Starlark cost) |

**V-Starlark is roughly tied with Lua, possibly slightly faster.**

The 3× gap between vflow gateway and Envoy gateway (66.7 µs vs 9.9 µs
plain-proxy overhead) is **structural to vflow's proxy plumbing**, NOT
the scripting language:

- gRPC connector framework: input encode (JSON → DynamicMessage → bytes)
  + outbound TCP/HTTP-2 + receive + response decode (bytes →
  DynamicMessage → JSON). ~30-40 µs.
- proto_encode FaaS for response: ~5-8 µs.
- Standard fastpath plan dispatch + variable store ops: ~10-20 µs.
- Workflow node-graph traversal: ~10 µs.

Envoy gets away with much less because:
- Tower stack routes without re-encoding the body
- Connection pool to upstream is hot
- No DynamicMessage roundtrip (just byte-pass)

## Reproduction

Same harness as 063 (see `063-vflow-gateway-vstarlark/README.md`)
with port 50071 and method `examples.GatewayPlain/Passthrough`.

```bash
ghz --insecure --proto ./proto/gateway.proto --import-paths ./proto \
    --call examples.GatewayPlain/Passthrough \
    --total 30000 --concurrency 512 --connections 32 \
    -d '{"tenant_id":"acme","trace_id":"t-001","payload":"hello"}' \
    127.0.0.1:50071
```

## Files

- `proto/gateway.proto` — combined proto with 3 services (062 Gateway, 063 GatewayProxy, 064 GatewayPlain)
- `gateway.desc.b64` — pre-computed FileDescriptorSet
- `workflow.yaml` — plain gateway (4 nodes, no scripting)
- Sister: `063-vflow-gateway-vstarlark/` — same workflow + V-Starlark scripting
- Sister: `062-fastpath-grpc-passthrough/` — shared upstream
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/064-vflow-gateway-plain/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: vflow-gateway-plain
  name: "vflow Plain Gateway (zero-copy byte forward)"
  description: |
    Plain gRPC forwarder workflow — pure byte pass-through, no
    body decode, no JSON ↔ proto roundtrip on either direction.
    Apple-to-apple with Envoy plain proxy.

    Activities (3): Trigger → forward → respond.

      - Trigger receives gRPC body as raw proto bytes (DataHandle).
      - `forward` Connector reads those bytes via `bytes_ref` into
        the `request` mapping; the fastpath dispatcher routes them
        through `execute_with_request_bytes` so the gRPC connector
        skips `json_to_dynamic_message` + `encode_to_vec` entirely.
      - `raw_response: true` makes the connector return the upstream
        proto wire bytes as `ConnectorOutput.data` with metadata
        `response_format: "raw_proto_bytes"`. Fastpath dispatch
        sees the marker, skips the wasted JSON parse on response,
        and writes the bytes directly to the `upstream_response`
        handle slot.
      - `respond` EndTrigger uses `bytes_ref` to return those bytes
        as the gRPC response body.

    Total: zero JSON serialize/deserialize, zero proto encode, zero
    proto decode anywhere on the request/response data path. The
    only JSON envelope work is for the small connector config
    fields (endpoint, descriptor_set_b64, service, method) — those
    are static literals, evaluated once per request as a small
    Map<String,Value>. A future optimization could bake those into
    the FastpathConnectorNode plan at upload time.

  dialect: vflow
  tags: [example, p0, grpc, gateway, connector, bench, fastpath, plain, zerocopy]

spec:
  activities:
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: grpc
        runtime_mode: fastpath
        grpc:
          service: "examples.GatewayPlain"
          method: "Passthrough"
          body_schema: "examples.GatewayMessage"
        response_framing: length_prefixed
        end_activity: respond
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    - id: forward
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: vastar.grpc
        operation: call
        timeout_ms: 5000
      input_mappings:
        - target: endpoint
          source: { language: literal, source: "http://127.0.0.1:50071" }
        - target: descriptor_set_b64
          source:
            language: literal
            source: ""
        - target: service
          source: { language: literal, source: "examples.Gateway" }
        - target: method
          source: { language: literal, source: "Passthrough" }
        # Request payload as RAW WIRE BYTES from the trigger body
        # handle. Fastpath dispatch detects `bytes_ref` on the
        # `request` target and routes the bytes through the
        # `execute_with_request_bytes` companion path — connector
        # skips proto encode entirely.
        - target: request
          source: { language: bytes_ref, source: "trigger_body" }
        # Connector returns the upstream's raw proto bytes as
        # ConnectorOutput.data; dispatch mirrors them into
        # `upstream_response`'s handle slot for `bytes_ref` below.
        - target: raw_response
          source: { language: literal, source: "true" }
      output_variable: upstream_response

    - id: respond
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response:
          language: bytes_ref
          source: "upstream_response"

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    - { id: f1, from: { node: trigger }, to: { node: forward } }
    - { id: f2, from: { node: forward }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f3, from: { node: respond }, to: { node: end } }

  variables:
    - { name: trigger_payload,   type: object }
    - { name: upstream_response, type: object }
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/065-fastpath-stream-prework-detached-usage/README.md">
# 065 Fastpath Stream Prework Detached Usage

This example is the documented version of the Acisku `/api/ai/analyze`
dogfooding pattern:

- `runtime_mode: fastpath` is declared on the webhook trigger.
- Auth, quota reads, and quota guard run before the streaming connector.
- The AI call uses `vastar.http` with `streaming: true`, `format: sse`,
  `dialect: openai`, connector-native `json_tap`, and the local
  `ai-endpoint-simulator` at `http://127.0.0.1:4545`.
- The streaming connector intentionally has no `output_variable`; the runtime
  forwards chunks to the client without collecting the full stream body.
- Usage accounting is a detached branch from the streaming connector, so it runs
  after stream acceptance without blocking the client response.
- The sqlite connection resolves through `pack://examples/acisku/primary`,
  provided by `examples-vflow/packs/acisku/pack.yaml`.

This is the local benchmark form of the pattern. Production packs should replace
the local x-user-uid fallback with Firebase/RS256 token verification.

The workflow is heavily commented because it is meant as an authoring guide.
Use it when building business endpoints that need request validation or quota
checks before an SSE/LLM response.

## Runtime shape

```text
Trigger
  -> auth_context
  -> quota_feature_context
  -> load_usage_count
  -> quota_gate
  -> call_ai_stream  --stream bytes--> client
       | detached
       v
     insert_usage_tracking
```

If quota is exceeded, the graph reaches `respond` before the stream connector
and returns the JSON quota error instead of opening the stream.

## Reproduce

```bash
SCENARIOS="065-fastpath-stream-prework-detached-usage" \
TOOLS="wrk" \
MODE=requests \
REQUESTS=100 \
bash benchmark-vflow/run-primary.sh
```
</file>

<file path="docs/provision-pattern/065-fastpath-stream-prework-detached-usage/workflow.yaml">
version: "3.0"
metadata:
  id: fastpath-stream-prework-detached-usage
  name: "Fastpath Stream With Prework And Detached Usage"
  description: "Acisku-style fastpath streaming endpoint: auth/quota prework, zero-copy SSE forwarding, and detached usage accounting."
  dialect: vflow
  tags: [fastpath, stream, sse, openai, vil_query, detached, authoring-guide]

spec:
  activities:
    # Fastpath is selected at Trigger level. This is important: authors should
    # not rely on runtime inference. The trigger also declares chunked framing
    # because a streaming connector will send response chunks to the client.
    - id: trigger
      activity_type: Trigger
      trigger_config:
        trigger_type: webhook
        runtime_mode: fastpath
        webhook_config:
          path: /examples/fastpath/stream-prework
          method: POST
        response_framing: chunked
        end_activity: respond
      output_variable: trigger_payload

    # This example is benchmark-local: the request may carry x-user-uid, and
    # otherwise falls back to a stable bench user. Production packs should
    # replace this with Firebase/RS256 verification and derive uid from the
    # verified token, not from a client-controlled header.
    - id: auth_context
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: uid
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: >
              has(trigger_payload.headers.x_user_uid) &&
              trigger_payload.headers.x_user_uid != "" ?
              trigger_payload.headers.x_user_uid :
              "bench-user"
      output_variable: auth

    # literal is the cheapest mapping language. Use it for constants such as
    # feature keys, connector URLs, static subjects, and fixed policy labels.
    - id: quota_feature_context
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: feature
          source: { language: literal, source: "financial_analysis" }
      output_variable: quota_context

    # Keep the example self-contained for the primary benchmark runner. In a
    # production pack this table is created by schema migration/bootstrap.
    - id: ensure_usage_table
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: "pack://examples/acisku/primary"
        operation: execute
      input_mappings:
        - target: sql
          source:
            language: literal
            source: >
              CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS usage_tracking (
                id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
                uid TEXT NOT NULL,
                feature TEXT NOT NULL,
                used_at TEXT DEFAULT (datetime('now'))
              )
      output_variable: usage_schema

    # DB access uses vil_query rather than hand-written SQL. The compiler emits
    # parameterized SQL plus ordered params. Runtime receives structured query
    # input, not string-concatenated SQL.
    - id: load_usage_count
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: "pack://examples/acisku/primary"
        operation: raw_query
      input_mappings:
        - target: query
          source:
            language: vil_query
            dialect: sqlite
            source: |
              select("usage_tracking")
                .count_as("used")
                .where_eq("uid", auth.uid)
                .where_eq("feature", quota_context.feature)
                .where_raw("used_at >= datetime('now', '-30 days')")
      output_variable: usage_count

    # V-CEL is appropriate here because the values are derived from prior
    # activity outputs. count_as returns one row, but defensive expressions are
    # still preferred when a query can return zero rows.
    - id: quota_gate
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: used
          source: { language: v-cel, source: "int(usage_count.rows[0].used)" }
        - target: limit
          source: { language: literal, source: "30" }
        - target: allowed
          source: { language: v-cel, source: "int(usage_count.rows[0].used) < 30" }
      output_variable: quota_gate

    # This Transform is reached only when the request is rejected before the
    # stream starts. It prepares the JSON payload that EndTrigger will return.
    - id: quota_exceeded_response
      activity_type: Transform
      input_mappings:
        - target: response
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: >
              {
                "_status": 403,
                "error": "quota_exceeded",
                "feature": quota_context.feature,
                "used": quota_gate.used,
                "limit": quota_gate.limit
              }
      output_variable: api_response

    # The streaming connector is the response producer. json_tap extracts
    # OpenAI-compatible delta content from each SSE data event inside the HTTP
    # connector, before chunks reach workflow-level transforms.
    #
    # There is intentionally no output_variable on this node. That keeps the
    # fastpath stream hot path from collecting the full response body. Add an
    # output_variable only if post-stream V-CEL really needs the whole content.
    - id: call_ai_stream
      activity_type: Connector
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: vastar.http
        operation: post
        streaming: true
        format: sse
        dialect: openai
        json_tap: "choices[0].delta.content"
        timeout_ms: 120000
      input_mappings:
        - target: url
          source:
            language: literal
            source: "http://127.0.0.1:4545/v1/chat/completions"
        - target: body
          source:
            language: v-cel
            source: >
              {
                "model": "gpt-4",
                "messages": [
                  {
                    "role": "system",
                    "content": "You are a local benchmark financial analysis assistant. Reply in concise Markdown."
                  },
                  {
                    "role": "user",
                    "content": string(trigger_payload.body.message) +
                      "\n\nFINANCIAL_CONTEXT_JSON:\n" +
                      string(trigger_payload.body.context)
                  }
                ],
                "temperature": 0.7,
                "max_completion_tokens": 4096,
                "stream": true
              }

    # Detached side effect. This branch is spawned after the stream connector is
    # accepted/closed and must not hold the client response open. Because the
    # branch only needs auth.uid and quota_context.feature, it does not require
    # the streamed response body.
    - id: insert_usage_tracking
      activity_type: Connector
      persistence: ssot
      connector_config:
        connector_ref: "pack://examples/acisku/primary"
        operation: raw_query
      input_mappings:
        - target: query
          source:
            language: vil_query
            dialect: sqlite
            source: |
              insert("usage_tracking")
                .insert_columns("uid, feature")
                .value(auth.uid)
                .value(quota_context.feature)
      output_variable: usage_insert

    # EndTrigger is still required so the graph has one client-response endpoint.
    # If quota fails before the stream starts, this response is evaluated and
    # returned. If call_ai_stream ran, the client already received stream bytes;
    # post-stream continuation does not evaluate this final_response.
    - id: respond
      activity_type: EndTrigger
      end_trigger_config:
        trigger_ref: trigger
        final_response: { language: v-cel, source: "api_response.response" }

    - id: end
      activity_type: End

    - id: usage_end
      activity_type: End

  flows:
    # Main response path: auth -> quota -> stream or reject.
    - { id: f1, from: { node: trigger }, to: { node: auth_context } }
    - { id: f2, from: { node: auth_context }, to: { node: quota_feature_context } }
    - { id: f3, from: { node: quota_feature_context }, to: { node: ensure_usage_table } }
    - { id: f4, from: { node: ensure_usage_table }, to: { node: load_usage_count } }
    - { id: f5, from: { node: load_usage_count }, to: { node: quota_gate } }
    - { id: f6, from: { node: quota_gate }, to: { node: call_ai_stream }, condition: "quota_gate.allowed", priority: 20 }
    - { id: f7, from: { node: quota_gate }, to: { node: quota_exceeded_response }, condition: "!quota_gate.allowed", priority: 10 }
    - { id: f8, from: { node: quota_exceeded_response }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f9, from: { node: call_ai_stream }, to: { node: respond } }
    - { id: f10, from: { node: respond }, to: { node: end } }

    # Detached branch: usage accounting is a background side effect. It is
    # attached to call_ai_stream so it can run after an accepted stream without
    # requiring a post-stream Transform that reads the full response body.
    - { id: f11, from: { node: call_ai_stream }, to: { node: insert_usage_tracking }, detached: true }
    - { id: f12, from: { node: insert_usage_tracking }, to: { node: usage_end } }
</file>

